12:["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-12","children":"The Doppler equation states that the frequency shift equals 2 × fo × v × cos(θ) / c, where fo is the transmitted frequency, v is the reflector velocity, θ is the Doppler angle, and c is the speed of sound. The key takeaway the SPI tests: the frequency shift is proportional to the cosine of the Doppler angle. At 0° (beam parallel to flow), you get maximum shift. At 90° (beam perpendicular), cos(90°) = 0 — so you detect no shift at all."}]
13:["$","div","02",{"className":"pt-4","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4 mb-3","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-mono text-2xl font-bold text-teal/30 shrink-0","children":"02"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-xl font-bold text-cream","children":"Doppler Angle Dependence"}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-12","children":"Angle correction is necessary when the beam cannot be aligned parallel to flow. Accuracy degrades significantly at angles above 60°. The SPI tests the concept that at large angles, small angle errors cause large velocity errors. Clinical implication: ARDMS expects you to know that 60° is the maximum clinically acceptable Doppler angle."}]]}]
14:["$","div","03",{"className":"pt-4","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4 mb-3","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-mono text-2xl font-bold text-teal/30 shrink-0","children":"03"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-xl font-bold text-cream","children":"Pulse Repetition Frequency & the Nyquist Limit"}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-12","children":"Pulsed-wave (PW) Doppler can only accurately measure frequency shifts up to half the pulse repetition frequency (PRF). This limit is the Nyquist limit. When a frequency shift exceeds the Nyquist limit, aliasing occurs — the displayed waveform wraps around and appears on the opposite side of the baseline. The SPI asks you to recognize aliasing and know how to correct it: increase PRF, lower frequency, increase Doppler angle, or use CW Doppler."}]]}]
15:["$","div","04",{"className":"pt-4","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4 mb-3","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-mono text-2xl font-bold text-teal/30 shrink-0","children":"04"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-xl font-bold text-cream","children":"Continuous Wave vs. Pulsed Wave Doppler"}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-12","children":"CW Doppler uses two crystals — one continuously transmitting, one receiving — which eliminates the Nyquist limit and allows measurement of any velocity. The tradeoff is range ambiguity: CW cannot localize where along the beam the signal originates. PW Doppler uses a single crystal with a sample volume gate, allowing precise depth selection at the cost of the Nyquist velocity limit."}]]}]
16:["$","div","05",{"className":"pt-4","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4 mb-3","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-mono text-2xl font-bold text-teal/30 shrink-0","children":"05"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-xl font-bold text-cream","children":"Spectral Broadening"}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-12","children":"Normal laminar flow produces a narrow spectral line with a clear spectral window. Turbulent flow causes a wide range of velocities at the sample site, broadening the spectral display and filling in the spectral window. The SPI expects you to recognize spectral broadening as an indicator of disturbed or turbulent flow — and to distinguish it from sample volume size effects."}]]}]
17:["$","div","06",{"className":"pt-4","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4 mb-3","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-mono text-2xl font-bold text-teal/30 shrink-0","children":"06"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-xl font-bold text-cream","children":"Color Flow & Power Doppler"}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"pl-12","children":"Color Doppler assigns color to mean Doppler frequency shift — red toward the transducer, blue away (by convention). It is angle-dependent. Power Doppler displays the amplitude (power) of the Doppler signal rather than frequency shift — making it sensitive to slow flow and angle-independent, at the cost of directional information. The SPI tests when to use each mode."}]]}]
18:["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold text-cream pt-4","children":"How to Study Doppler for the SPI"}]
19:["$","p",null,{"children":"Doppler physics is most effectively learned through active recall — not rereading. Use flashcards that prompt you to recall the Doppler equation, the Nyquist limit formula, and the aliasing correction strategies. Understand the tradeoffs (CW vs. PW, color vs. power) rather than memorizing tables."}]
1a:["$","p",null,{"children":"SonoPrep's flashcard deck includes dedicated Doppler cards built by practicing RDCS and RVT sonographers who use these principles in the clinical lab daily."}]
